Here is the `getControlPointsU` method for the `NurbsSurface` class, which returns an array of control points along the U direction:

```javascript
class NurbsSurface {
    constructor(controlPointsU, controlPointsV, knotsU, knotsV) {
        this.controlPointsU = controlPointsU;
        this.controlPointsV = controlPointsV;
        this.knotsU = knotsU;
        this.knotsV = knotsV;
    }

    getControlPointsU() {
        return this.controlPointsU;
    }
}
```

This method is straightforward, as it simply returns the `controlPointsU` array stored in the class instance. The constructor initializes the `NurbsSurface` object with control points along both U and V directions, as well as their corresponding knot vectors. By encapsulating the data within the class, we maintain encapsulation and avoid polluting the global scope with unnecessary variables.
